{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b11f3d97-0b22-4b27-9458-42debfedc057","content":"Add a `.vscode/mcp.json` file to your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- `type: \"stdio\"` means Copilot communicates with your server via stdin/stdout\n- `command` + `args` tell VS Code how to launch your server\n- The server name (`my-mcp-server`) is how it appears in Copilot's tool list\n\nAfter adding the file, open the Command Palette → **MCP: List Servers** to verify it's detected. Copilot agent mode will automatically discover the tools your server exposes.\n\nIf your server needs environment variables, add an `\"env\"` field:\n\n```json\n\"env\": { \"SOME_VAR\": \"value\" }\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"21d086b1-51dc-439d-b9a5-e23d3390bf34","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to know how to configure `mcp.json` to use their C# MCP server with GitHub Copilot in VS Code agent mode. Let me provide a concise answer based on my knowledge of VS Code MCP configuration.","outputTokens":316,"requestId":"2C10:217274:2BE04ED:303595E:69FD3638"},"id":"bedc00d6-8e93-4a8f-841e-4de4e47599db","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:02:58.091Z","parentId":"32009407-f721-4ebb-85ec-52e7ef4cc99c"}
